== History ==

=== Origins ===

According to a document titled "Document Showing Shrine Origins and History," attached to the official 1953 registration under the Religious Corporations Act<ref name="yuisho">Document Showing Shrine Origins and History</ref>:

{{Quotation|In the 8th month of the 2nd year of {{ill|Yōrō|ja|養老}} ({{Refnest|group="Note"|According to a wooden board on the premises, the transfer occurred in {{ill|Wadō 3|ja|和銅3年}} ({{ill|711|ja|711年}})<ref name="kiannai"/>.}}), the enshrined deity of Asuka Shrine in {{ill|Asuka, Nara|ja|飛鳥村}}, Takaichi District, Yamato Province, was transferred to the hill of Asuka in the Shijō Nanabō (4th Avenue, 7th Ward) of the new capital of Heijō, as the tutelary shrine of the {{ill|Gangō-ji|ja|元興寺}} temple in Nanto. This marked the founding of the present Asuka Shrine. In the medieval period, as Gangō-ji fell into decline, the shrine also diminished and was relocated to a corner of Kyōbate, as it remains today.{{Refnest|group="Note"|According to a wooden board on-site, the relocation to Kyōbate occurred after the {{ill|Bunmei uprisings|ja|土一揆}} during the {{ill|Hōtoku era|ja|宝徳}} (15th century) or {{ill|Tenbun era|ja|天文}} (16th century)<ref name="kiannai"/>. A paper signboard on the premises says it happened in {{ill|Ōan 2|ja|応安2年}} ({{ill|1369|ja|1369年}})<ref name="kamiannai">Paper board on-site</ref>. The Nara City History adopts the Ōan 2 date{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}.}}

In {{ill|Bunsei 9|ja|文政9年}}, {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|菅原道真}} was added as a deity, and the shrine came to be popularly known as Kōbaiden Shrine. The {{ill|Daijōin|ja|大乗院}} abbots of Gangō-ji oversaw its worship. In the Meiji period, it became the ujigami (local tutelary shrine) of the Kyōbate area of Nara City under the name Kōbaiden Shrine. However, the old religious corporation under that name was dissolved and the shrine reverted to its historic name of Asuka Shrine, becoming a new religious corporation under the postwar Religious Corporations Act.

The Nara City and Prefectural histories issued thereafter follow this narrative{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History 5: Shrines|page=268}}.

=== Changes in Records and Deities in the Early Modern Period ===

However, no early modern or earlier records mention that this shrine moved from Asuka with Gangō-ji. Also, while the origin document claims that Tenjin (Sugawara no Michizane) was enshrined in {{ill|Bunsei 9|ja|文政9年}} ({{ill|1826|ja|1826年}}), older records say Tenjin was enshrined to commemorate Kyōbate Village’s victory in a water dispute in the {{ill|17th century|ja|17世紀}}{{sfn|Kadokawa Dictionary of Place Names|page=397}}.

Early documents and maps show various discrepancies in the shrine's name and enshrined deities:

