'''Asuka Shrine''' (Asuka Jinja) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|1=Shinto shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q845945}} located in {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|1=Nara Prefecture|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q131287}}, {{ill|Nara (city)|ja|奈良市|1=Nara (city)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q169134}}, {{ill|Hokukyōbatechō|ja|北京終町}}. It is commonly referred to as '''Kyōbate Tenjinsha''', and also known as '''Kōbaiden Shrine''' and '''Heijōza Asuka Shrine'''{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History 5: Shrines|page=268}}.

== Deities ==

According to the Nara City History, the shrine enshrines the following five kami{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}, although there are alternate traditions{{Refnest|group="Note"|According to a wooden information board on the grounds, the five kami are:<br>* {{ill|Asuka Sanbime no Mikoto|ja|明日香三比女命}}<br>* {{ill|Ame no Kotoshironushi|ja|天之事代主命}}<br>* {{ill|Kayanarumi no Mikoto|ja|賀夜奈留美命}}<br>* {{ill|Usutaki-hime no Mikoto|ja|宇須太岐比女命}}<br>* {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|1=Sugawara no Michizane|2=ja|3=菅原道真|ja|贈太政大臣道眞公|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q382005}}<ref name="kiannai">Wooden board on-site</ref>}}.
* {{ill|Kotoshironushi|ja|事代主神|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q8009611}}
* {{ill|Kayanarumi no Mikoto|ja|加夜奈留美命}}
* {{ill|Usutaki-hime no Mikoto|ja|宇須多岐比女命}}
* {{ill|Fusokuru-hime no Mikoto|ja|不足留比女命}}
* {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|1=Sugawara no Michizane|2=ja|3=菅原道真|ja|菅原道真|1=Sugawara no Michizane|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q382005}}

== History ==

=== Origins ===

According to a document titled "Document Showing Shrine Origins and History," attached to the official 1953 registration under the Religious Corporations Act<ref name="yuisho">Document Showing Shrine Origins and History</ref>:

{{Quotation|In the 8th month of the 2nd year of {{ill|Yōrō|ja|養老|1=Yōrō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q1373061}} ({{Refnest|group="Note"|According to a wooden board on the premises, the transfer occurred in {{ill|Wadō 3|ja|和銅3年}} ({{ill|711|ja|711年|1=AD 711|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q23519}})<ref name="kiannai"/>.}}), the enshrined deity of Asuka Shrine in {{ill|Asuka, Nara|ja|飛鳥村|1=Q11665974|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11665974}}, Takaichi District, Yamato Province, was transferred to the hill of Asuka in the Shijō Nanabō (4th Avenue, 7th Ward) of the new capital of Heijō, as the tutelary shrine of the {{ill|Gangō-ji|ja|元興寺|1=Gangō-ji|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q1203099}} temple in Nanto. This marked the founding of the present Asuka Shrine. In the medieval period, as Gangō-ji fell into decline, the shrine also diminished and was relocated to a corner of Kyōbate, as it remains today.{{Refnest|group="Note"|According to a wooden board on-site, the relocation to Kyōbate occurred after the {{ill|Bunmei uprisings|ja|土一揆|1=Tsuchi Ikki|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11422932}} during the {{ill|Hōtoku era|ja|宝徳|1=Hōtoku|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q1143606}} (15th century) or {{ill|Tenbun era|ja|天文|1=Tenmon|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q21096812}} (16th century)<ref name="kiannai"/>. A paper signboard on the premises says it happened in {{ill|Ōan 2|ja|応安2年}} ({{ill|1369|ja|1369年|1=1369|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q6211}})<ref name="kamiannai">Paper board on-site</ref>. The Nara City History adopts the Ōan 2 date{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}.}}

In {{ill|Bunsei 9|ja|文政9年}}, {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|1=Sugawara no Michizane|2=ja|3=菅原道真|ja|菅原道真|1=Sugawara no Michizane|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q382005}} was added as a deity, and the shrine came to be popularly known as Kōbaiden Shrine. The {{ill|Daijōin|ja|大乗院|1=Daijō-in|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q16766994}} abbots of Gangō-ji oversaw its worship. In the Meiji period, it became the ujigami (local tutelary shrine) of the Kyōbate area of Nara City under the name Kōbaiden Shrine. However, the old religious corporation under that name was dissolved and the shrine reverted to its historic name of Asuka Shrine, becoming a new religious corporation under the postwar Religious Corporations Act.

The Nara City and Prefectural histories issued thereafter follow this narrative{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History 5: Shrines|page=268}}.

=== Changes in Records and Deities in the Early Modern Period ===

However, no early modern or earlier records mention that this shrine moved from Asuka with Gangō-ji. Also, while the origin document claims that Tenjin (Sugawara no Michizane) was enshrined in {{ill|Bunsei 9|ja|文政9年}} ({{ill|1826|ja|1826年|1=1826|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q7004}}), older records say Tenjin was enshrined to commemorate Kyōbate Village’s victory in a water dispute in the {{ill|17th century|ja|17世紀|1=17th century|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q7016}}{{sfn|Kadokawa Dictionary of Place Names|page=397}}.

