=== Similar Origins at Nearby Shrines ===

The tradition that this shrine was the tutelary shrine of Gangō-ji transferred from Asuka during the establishment of Heijō-kyō is also found in Edo-period records regarding nearby shrines such as {{ill|Isagawa Shrine (Nara City Nishishinmachi)|ja|率川神社 (奈良市西新屋町)|1=Isagawa Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q48761131}} about 400 meters north in {{ill|Nishishinmachi, Nara|ja|西新屋町|1=Nishinoshin'yachō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q28686454}}, and {{ill|Hakusan Shrine (Nara City Gangoji Town)|ja|白山神社 (奈良市元興寺町)|1=Hakusan Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q48761897}} in {{ill|Gangoji Town|ja|元興寺町|1=Gangōji-chō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q28687279}}{{sfn|Narabōmoku Sakkai|p=22,58}}{{sfn|Gangoji Origin Record|p=153–155}}. However, no sources confirm these shrines moved to Kyōbate.

== Shrine Grounds ==

[[File:Nara Kyobate Temjin Honden1.jpg|thumb|150px|Main Hall]]
[[File:Kasuga-taisha sanjyuhassho jinja.jpg|thumb|150px|Reference: Kasuga Shrine Sub-shrine Sanjūhassho Shrine]]
[[File:Kasuganocho, Nara, Nara Prefecture 630-8212, Japan - panoramio - jetsun (4).jpg|thumb|150px|Reference: Kasuga Shrine Sub-shrine Mizutani Shrine]]

=== Main Hall ===

The main hall was relocated from a former sub-shrine of {{ill|Kasuga Shrine|ja|春日大社|1=Kasuga-taisha|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q714559}} in a practice known as “Kasuga Utsushi.” There are two theories about which sub-shrine was moved: one identifies it as the {{ill|Sanjūhassho Shrine|ja|三十八所神社}}{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History 8: Architecture|page=912}}, the other as {{ill|Mizutani Shrine (Nara City)|ja|水谷神社|1=Mizutani Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11549203}}{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History 5: Shrines|page=268}}.<ref group="Note">As of 2018, structural comparisons such as pillar placement suggest resemblance to Sanjūhassho Shrine.</ref> If it is Mizutani Shrine, the relocation is thought to have occurred in {{ill|Bunsei 9|ja|文政9年}} ({{ill|1826|ja|1826年|1=1826|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q7004}}){{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History 5: Shrines|page=268}}. The structure is a {{ill|Sangensha-zukuri|ja|三間社造}} with a copper-sheet roof{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}. Decorative elements such as kenbamon (sword-hilt crests) are seen on the lintels{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}.

=== Sub-shrines ===

* {{ill|Munakata Shrine|ja|宗像神社|1=Munakata Shrines|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11451876}} (Deity: {{ill|Ichikishimahime no Mikoto|ja|市杵島姫命|1=Ichikishima-hime|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11059454}}) – formerly located within the grounds of {{ill|Kōdaiji (Kyoto)|ja|高台寺|1=Kōdai-ji|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q2702064}} in Hanazono{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History 5: Shrines|page=268}}.
* Ōkuninushi Shrine (Deities: {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主命}}, {{ill|Hiruko|ja|蛭子命|1=Hiruko|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q1067028}}) – formerly within {{ill|Gokurakubō|ja|禅定院（極楽坊）}} of Gangō-ji{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History 5: Shrines|page=268}}.
* {{ill|Kotohira Shrine|ja|金刀比羅神社|1=Kotohira shrines|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11646488}} (Deity: {{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主命}}) – formerly at {{ill|Shōtōin|ja|小塔院|1=Shōtō-in Temple|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11459543}}{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}{{sfn|Nara Prefectural History 5: Shrines|page=268}}.<ref group="Note">As of 2018, the enshrined deity is indicated as Konohanasakuya-hime.</ref>
* {{ill|Tsukihara Myōjinsha|ja|月原明神社}} – A small shrine once by the pond called Amida-ike; relocated in {{ill|1982|ja|昭和57年|1=1982|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q2436}}, June, by the Kyōbate Agricultural Union{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}.
* {{ill|Shichibenten Shrine|ja|七弁天社}} – Also relocated from the bank of Amida-ike{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}.

Other enshrined deities include {{ill|Emperor Sutoku|ja|崇徳天皇|1=Emperor Sutoku|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q349287}}{{sfn|Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Edition|page=147}}.

== Practical Information ==

; Address
